93. Ille supercilium] Here follows a gra- phic description of the way these wretches proceed. One blaeks his eyebrows with soot, and extends them by the same means, using a crisping pin for the purpose. Pliny (H.N. xxviii. 11) says that the Romans used bears'grease for the purpose of restoring the hair of the head and eyebrows, “cum fungis lucernarum et fuligine quae est in rostris earum,'’ that is, with the burnt part of the wick, and the soot which accumulates on the rim of the lamp. ‘Obliqua acu ’ means with a needle drawn across it.
